# How to use AI Source Scraper (v1.4.1)

A step-by-step guide for capturing cited web sources from Claude, Gemini,
and ChatGPT. There are two ways to run the tool — the **browser extension /
userscript** (a panel with buttons) and the **console-buffered build** (a
script you paste into the browser console). Both produce the same data.

> **Before you start — login note.** ChatGPT and Gemini work while logged
> out (usage limits may apply). Claude.ai requires an account for any
> conversation, so captures from Claude are always from a logged-in
> session. This matters only if your design compares logged-in vs
> logged-out behaviour.

---

## A. Choose your research design first

The tool records two research designs, set with the **Capture mode** toggle.
Pick the one that matches your question:

- **Longitudinal** — you are tracking the *same* prompt over time or across
  a conversational sequence (does the answer, or its sources, drift?).
- **Comparative** — you are comparing *different* prompts or conditions at
  one point in time (does source selection change with framing or search
  mode?).

The mode you choose decides which metadata field you fill in:

| Capture mode | Field shown | Also shown |
|---|---|---|
| **Longitudinal** | **Prompt condition** — Isolated / Initial / Follow-up | Search condition |
| **Comparative** | **Prompt framing** — Underspecified / Program / Anti-program / Ambiguous | Search condition |

---

## B. Using the browser extension (or userscript)

**Step 1 — Open a source-bearing response.**
On Claude, Gemini, or ChatGPT, send a prompt that triggers web search, and
open the response's **sources / activity panel** so the cited links are
visible on screen.

**Step 2 — Open the AI Source Scraper panel.**
It appears as a floating panel at the bottom-right of the page. (If you
installed the userscript, it appears the same way.)

**Step 3 — Set the Capture mode.**
Toggle **Longitudinal** (default) or **Comparative** at the top of the
panel. The field below (Prompt condition or Prompt framing) changes to match.

**Step 4 — Fill in the fields.**
- **Session label** — a short code for this capture, e.g. `medium_p0_cold`.
  Convention: `{topic}_{prompt_id}_{thread_state}` (see "Naming your
  captures").
- **Prompt condition** *(Longitudinal)* or **Prompt framing**
  *(Comparative)* — pick the option describing this capture.
- **Search condition** — AI search or Agentic AI search.
- **AI fieldwork observations** *(optional)* — jot down anything you notice
  (anomalies, response structure, context). These travel with your data.

**Step 5 — Scan.**
Click **Scan and add to session**. The tool scrolls the source panel,
collects every cited link with its metadata, de-duplicates, and adds the
rows to the current session buffer. The summary shows how many sources this
capture found and the running buffer total.

**Step 6 — Repeat for each capture.**
Send the next prompt (or open the next condition), adjust the fields if
needed, and click **Scan and add to session** again. Captures accumulate.
The buffer survives an accidental page reload.

**Step 7 — Download.**
Open **Download files separately** to reveal:
- **Download all (CSV + JSON + TXT)** — one click, all three files.
- **CSV**, **JSON**, **TXT** — individual files.

The `.txt` is your fieldwork-observations companion, with a citation block
and a session header. All three files share one filename stamp so they stay
matched.

**Step 8 — Start a fresh session** when you're done: **clear buffer**
(it warns you first if you have unsaved observations).

---

## C. Using the console-buffered build

For when you prefer no panel, or want to script captures. Same data, same
schema.

**Step 1 — Open the browser console.**
On the AI platform's page, open DevTools → Console (macOS: ⌥⌘J, Windows/
Linux: Ctrl+Shift+J). Paste the entire contents of
`ai-source-scraper-console-buffered.js` once and press Enter. Nothing
downloads yet — it installs a small `grab` API.

**Step 2 — Set your research design and variables** (all optional; sensible
defaults apply):

```js
grab.mode('comparative')            // 'longitudinal' (default) | 'comparative'
grab.search('agentic_ai_search')    // 'ai_search' | 'agentic_ai_search'
grab.framing('program')             // Comparative: underspecified|program|anti_program|ambiguous
grab.promptCondition('initial')     // Longitudinal: isolated|initial|follow_up ('' = infer from label)
grab.notes('Observations for this session…')
```

In **comparative** mode `prompt_condition` is left blank automatically; in
**longitudinal** mode `prompt_framing` is left blank — matching the panel.

**Step 3 — Open a response's source panel, then scan:**

```js
grab('medium_p0_cold')              // the string is your session label / file_id
grab('medium_p0_cold', 'panel slow to load')   // optional per-scan note
```

Each `grab(...)` appends to the buffer. Repeat after each prompt.

**Step 4 — Check progress anytime:**

```js
grab.status()     // buffer summary: rows, captures, domains, current mode
```

**Step 5 — Download:**

```js
grab.all()        // CSV + JSON + TXT (one filename stamp)
grab.csv()        // or individually
grab.json()
grab.txt()
```

**Step 6 — Start fresh:**

```js
grab.clear()      // empties the buffer and observations
```

